## 🔬 Test Smell Audit — testsmells.org 19-Smell Academic Catalog

**File:** `OrderService.Tests/OrderProcessorTests.cs`  
**Framework:** MSTest 4.1.0 / .NET 10  
**Reference:** Peruma et al., "tsDetect: An Open Source Test Smells Detection Tool," ESEC/FSE 2020

---

### Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High     | 4           | 4              |
| Medium   | 4           | 4              |
| Low      | 1           | all (class-level) |
| **Total**| **9**       | **8 of 9 methods** |

---

### High-Severity Findings

#### 1. Conditional Test Logic _(Smell #1)_

**Method:** `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (line 24)  
**Evidence:** `if/else` branching inside the test body — one path is never verified.

```csharp
// ❌ Smelly
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
```

**Fix:** Split into two deterministic tests with controlled inputs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_Over100_SetsPremiumStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("EXPENSIVE", 1) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_Under100_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("CHEAP", 1) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** One branch may never execute — hidden coverage gap.

---

#### 2. Assertion-Free Test / Unknown Test _(Smell #4)_

**Method:** `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)  
**Evidence:** No assertion, no `Assert.ThrowsException`, no `[ExpectedException]`.

```csharp
// ❌ Smelly — passes even if ProcessOrder is completely broken (as long as it doesn't throw)
processor.ProcessOrder(order);
```

**Fix:** Assert the observable outcome:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);

    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False confidence — code coverage goes up but nothing is actually verified.

---

#### 3. Sleepy Test _(Smell #3)_

**Method:** `ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent` (line 91)  
**Evidence:** `Thread.Sleep(2000)` — hardcoded 2-second wait.

```csharp
// ❌ Smelly
processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);
Thread.Sleep(2000);
Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
```

**Fix:** Use a polling/wait helper or make the fake synchronously completable:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    await processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);

    Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Non-deterministic failures under load; adds 2 s to every suite run (Camara et al. 2021 link to flakiness).

